modern day, current relationships of this generation, thus making it very relatable for the millennials.\nIn fact, any amateur music enthusiast, who seeks proficiency in guitar playing, could use this song as basics to get a hold of the chord progression, or the strumming pattern. Also, a professional guitar player could add quite a few guitar licks and solos to give the song a little twist and make it their own.\nAs far as vocal competency is considered, this song usually goes into a linearity, with not a lot of variations required, which would look like or give a feel of an easy song to sing but requires a high emotional resonance and tonal quality to make an lyrically sad and sappy song into an upbeat and foot tapping song to listen to on the radio. All in all, this is an effortless song but what it requires is for the audience to “feel” something, to make the song more heart-rending.\nUsually, songs that are catchy and easy to pick up usually become a fan favorite, taking an example of J Star’s Main Tera Boyfriend, the chorus isn’t complicated and the melody is one of the easiest to remember, thus it gains an overnight success, most of the people especially in this generation don’t consider deep meaning lyrics or complicated composition as a niche for a good song; a good song (for them) shouldn’t be a task to remember, a good song is such that can be sung by college friends during a car trip, that makes the listener come back to it again and again and Tera Ghata fulfills all the requirements of a good song.\nThe original scale of the song is C#m (C sharp minor chord), you can use the capo on the 4th fret of your guitar to make the song easy to play on guitar. By adding the capo the scale of this song becomes Am from the C#m. If you’re a beginner and going to play Tera ghata guitar chords then we highly recommend using the capo as the intro of this song is a little hard to play. If we talk about the Strumming pattern then you just have to do strum in D UD UD UD U