ize of the pointer is 2 bytes in 16-bit platform.\r\n\r\nBut in Linux, the output will be 4, 1 because the size of the pointer is 4 bytes.\r\n\r\nThis difference is due to the platform dependency of C compiler.','2, 1','4, 1','2, 2','4, 2','Yes'),(20,20,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    void *vp;\r\n    char ch=74, *cp=\"JACK\";\r\n    int j=65;\r\n    vp=&ch;\r\n    printf(\"%c\", *(char*)vp);\r\n    vp=&j;\r\n    printf(\"%c\", *(int*)vp);\r\n    vp=cp;\r\n    printf(\"%s\", (char*)vp+2);\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','D\r\n\r\nPointer always store integer value so cp will store the memory address of location where string \"jack \" is stored.\r\n\r\nStep 1 : vp = &ch;\r\n/*Will store address of ch in vp so while we print content in printf it will print asccii value of 74 i.e \"J\"*/\r\n\r\nStep 2 : vp = &j;\r\n/* It will assign address of j to vp again it will print ascii value of 65 as \"A\"*/\r\n\r\nStep 3 : vp = cp;\r\n/* In this step cp is pointing to memory locatioon where string jack is stored and we r incrementing it by two so it will point to \"C\" from sring \"JACK\" and since we hava given %S in printf so it will print content from c onwords ie \"CK\"*/\r\n\r\nSo final combined output will be JACK.','JCK','J65K','JAK','JACK','Yes'),(21,21,'Which of the following function sets first n characters of a string to a given character?','B\r\n\r\nchar *strnset(char *s, int ch, size_t n); Sets the first n characters of s to ch','strinit()','strnset()','strset()','strcset()','Yes'),(22,22,'If the two strings are identical, then strcmp() function returns','D\r\n\r\n strcmp(const char *s1, const char*s2);\r\n\r\nThe strcmp return an int value that is\r\n\r\nif s1 < s2 returns a value < 0\r\n\r\nif s1 == s2 returns 0\r\n\r\nif s1 > s2 returns a value > 0','-1','1','yes','0','Yes'),(23,23,'How will you print \\n on the screen?','D\r\n\r\nThe statement printf(\"\\\\n\"); prints \'\\n\' on the screen.','printf(\"\\