ce it prints \"Hello World\".','Hello World','Hello','WorldHello','World','Yes'),(28,28,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n#include<string.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    printf(\"%d\\n\", strlen(\"123456\"));\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','The function strlen returns the number of characters in the given string.\r\n\r\nTherefore, strlen(\"123456\") returns 6.\r\n\r\nHence the output of the program is \"6\".','12','6','7','2','Yes'),(29,29,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    printf(5+\"Good Morning\\n\");\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','printf(5+\"Good Morning\\n\"); It skips the 5 characters and prints the given string.\r\n\r\nHence the output is \"Morning\"','Good Morning','Good','M','Morning','Yes'),(30,30,'What will be the output of the program If characters \'a\', \'b\' and \'c\' enter are supplied as input?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    void fun();\r\n    fun();\r\n    printf(\"\\n\");\r\n    return 0;\r\n}\r\nvoid fun()\r\n{\r\n    char c;\r\n    if((c = getchar())!= \'\\n\')\r\n        fun();\r\n    printf(\"%c\", c);\r\n}','Step 1: void fun(); This is the prototype for the function fun().\r\n\r\nStep 2: fun(); The function fun() is called here.\r\n\r\nThe function fun() gets a character input and the input is terminated by an enter key(New line character). It prints the given character in the reverse order.\r\n\r\nThe given input characters are \"abc\"','abc abc','bca','Infinite loop','cba','Yes'),(31,31,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n#include<string.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    static char str1[] = \"dills\";\r\n    static char str2[20];\r\n    static char str3[] = \"Daffo\";\r\n    int i;\r\n    i = strcmp(strcat(str3, strcpy(str2, str1)), \"Daffodills\");\r\n    printf(\"%d\\n\", i);\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','B\r\n\r\nstrcpy(str2,str1) : here \"dills\" will be copied to str2.\r\nHence str2 contains \" dills\"\r\n\r\nstrcat(str3,str2) : \"dills\" will be concatenated with \"daffo\"\r\nHence str3 contains \" Daffodills \".\r\n\r\nAt last strcmp compares with the string str3 with \"Daffodills\" and pass the value \"0\" since the string matches.','1','0','2','4','Yes'),(32,32,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n#include<string.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    static char s[] = \"Hello!\";\r\n    printf(\"%d\\n\", *(s+strlen(s)));\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','A\r\n\r\nThe expression *(s+strlen(s)) will yeild *(s+6), because s[]=\"hello!\"; contains 6 characters, so the length is 6.\r\n\r\nand the expression *(s+6)= s[6]. (acc. to pointers to array theory).\r\n\r\nnow in a string the last element/bit always contains \'\\0\'.\r\nso, s[0]= \'H\'\r\ns[1]= \'e\'\r\ns[2]= \'l\'\r\ns[3]= \'l\'\r\ns[4]= \'o\'\r\ns[5]= \'!\'\r\ns[6]= \'\\0\'\r\n\r\nhence the output gives zero value because ascii value of \\0 is zero.','0','8','16','Error','Yes'),(33,33,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    int i;\r\n    char a[] = \"\\0\";\r\n    if(printf(\"%s\", a))\r\n        printf(\"The string is empty\\n\");\r\n    else\r\n        printf(\"The string is not empty\\n\");\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','B\r\n\r\nThe function printf() returns the number of charecters printed on the console.\r\n\r\nStep 1: char a[] = \"\\0\"; The variable a is declared as an array of characters and it initialized with \"\\0\". It denotes that the string is empty.\r\n\r\nStep 2: if(printf(\"%s\", a)) The printf() statement does not print anything, so it returns \'0\'(zero). Hence the if condition is failed.\r\n\r\nIn the else part it prints \"The string is not empty\".','The string is empty','The string is not em','No output','0','Yes'),(34,34,'If char=1, int=4, and float=4 bytes size, What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    char ch = \'A\';\r\n    printf(\"%d, %d, %d\", sizeof(ch), sizeof(\'A\'), sizeof(3.14f));\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','B\r\n\r\nStep 1: char ch = \'A\'; The variable ch is declared as an character type and initialized with value \'A\'.\r\n\r\nStep 2:\r\n\r\nprintf(\"%d, %d, %d\", sizeof(ch), sizeof(\'A\'), sizeof(3.14));\r\n\r\nThe sizeof function returns the size of the given expression.\r\n\r\nsizeof(ch) becomes sizeof(char). The size of char is 1 byte.\r\n\r\nsizeof(\'A\') becomes sizeof(65). The size of int is 4 bytes (as mentioned in the question).\r\n\r\nsizeof(3.14f). The size of float is 4 bytes.\r\n\r\nHence the output of the program is 1, 4, 4','1, 2, 4','1, 4, 4','2, 2, 4','2, 4, 8','Yes'),(35,35,'If the size of pointer is 32 bits What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    char a[] = \"Visual C++\";\r\n    char *b = \"Visual C++\";\r\n    printf(\"%d, %d\\n\", sizeof(a), sizeof(b));\r\n    printf(\"%d, %d\", sizeof(*a), sizeof(*b));\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','C\r\n\r\nchar a[] has 10 characters + one escape character= 10+1=11 bytes\r\n\r\npointer *b have size 32 bits= 4 byte\r\n\r\n*a points to first character of word(i.e. \'V\')= 1 byte\r\n*b points to first character of word(i.e \'V\')= 1 byte\r\n\r\nSo answer prints:\r\n11 4\r\n1 1','10, 2 2, 2','10, 4 1, 2','11, 4 1, 1','12, 2 2, 2','Yes'),(36,36,'. 	\r\nWhat will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    char str1[] = \"Hello\";\r\n    char str2[10];\r\n    char *t, *s;\r\n    s = str1;\r\n    t = str2;\r\n    while(*t=*s)\r\n        *t++ = *s++;\r\n    printf(\"%s\\n\", str2);\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','A\r\n\r\nHere s will points to the beginig of string str1.\r\n\r\nAnd t will points to the begining address of string str2.\r\n\r\nIn while loop we are copying the elements from str1 to str2 using pointers s and t untill end of string is reached.','Hello','HelloHello','No output','ello','Yes'),(37,37,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\