 = \"Hello\"; The variable str2 is declared as an array of characters and initialized with a string \"Hello\".\r\n\r\nWe have use strcmp(s1,s2) function to compare strings.\r\n\r\nStep 3: if(str1 == str2) here the address of str1 and str2 are compared. The address of both variable is not same. Hence the if condition is failed.\r\n\r\nStep 4: At the else part it prints \"Unequal\".','Equal','Unequal','Error','None of above','Yes'),(40,40,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    char t;\r\n    char *p1 = \"India\", *p2;\r\n    p2=p1;\r\n    p1 = \"Today\";\r\n    printf(\"%s %s\\n\", p1, p2);\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','B\r\n\r\nStep 1: char *p1 = \"India\", *p2; The variable p1 and p2 is declared as an pointer to a character value and p1 is assigned with a value \"India\".\r\n\r\nStep 2: p2=p1; The value of p1 is assigned to variable p2. So p2 contains \"India\".\r\n\r\nStep 3: p1 = \"Today\"; The p1 is assigned with a string \"Today\"\r\n\r\nStep 4: printf(\"%s %s\\n\", p1, p2); It prints the value of p1 and p2.','India Today','Today India','India India','Today Today','Yes'),(41,41,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n#include<string.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    int i, n;\r\n    char *x=\"Alice\";\r\n    n = strlen(x);\r\n    *x = x[n];\r\n    for(i=0; i<=n; i++)\r\n    {\r\n        printf(\"%s \", x);\r\n        x++;\r\n    }\r\n    printf(\"\\n\", x);\r\n    return 0;\r\n}','D\r\n\r\nIf you compile and execute this program in windows platform with Turbo C, it will give \"lice ice ce e\".\r\n\r\nIt may give different output in other platforms (depends upon compiler and machine). The online C compiler given in this site will give the Option C as output (it runs on Linux platform).','Alice','ecilA','Alice lice ice ce e','lice ice ce e','Yes'),(42,42,'What will be the output of the program ?\r\n\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n\r\nint main()\r\n{\r\n    int i, a[] = {2, 4, 6, 8, 10};\r\n 